        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 5-year-old girl from the Czech Republic who is brought in by her parent with an acute sore throat after a night of fever and poor sleep, appearing tired and drowsy today [MEDDIALOG:J03.9:7]. She complains that her throat hurts and says her belly hurts as well [MEDDIALOG:J03.9:7]. The illness has been short in duration, with fever starting two nights ago, improving temporarily after paracetamol, then recurring overnight [MEDDIALOG:J03.9:7].\n\nOn examination, {patientName} looks uncomfortable but interactive, sitting close to her parent and swallowing cautiously because of throat pain and trouble swallowing that fit tonsillitis symptoms [MEDLINEPLUS:J03.9]. Her tonsils are red and swollen, consistent with inflammation of the tonsils [MEDLINEPLUS:J03.9]. The overall picture is that of tonsillitis [SNOMED:J03.9].\n\nAt home, {patientName} is an active kindergarten-aged child who usually plays with toys, draws, and spends time with her family; today she is less playful because of fever and throat pain [MEDDIALOG:J03.9:7]. She lives with her parents, has regular close contact with other children, and is in the age group in which tonsillitis is common, especially in children over age two and bacterial causes are more common in ages 5 to 15 [MEDLINEPLUS:J03.9]."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:752ecf3a-f560-4ed8-bff2-a4fbe613158c",
