        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a previously healthy 5-year-old girl with no known chronic medical conditions by history. She has had an acute febrile illness over the last two days, with fever that improved after paracetamol and then returned overnight, followed by sore throat, sleep disruption, drowsiness, and stomach pain [MEDDIALOG:J03.9:7]. There is no evidence provided of prior hospitalizations, surgery, or recurrent tonsillar disease.\n\nShe is in the common pediatric age range for tonsillitis, as this condition is most common in children over age two, and bacterial tonsillitis is more common in children ages 5 to 15 [MEDLINEPLUS:J03.9]. She likely has frequent exposure to common respiratory pathogens through routine contact with other children, and the viruses and bacteria that cause tonsillitis are contagious [MEDLINEPLUS:J03.9]."
          }
        ]
      }
